OKONOMI serves the perfect breakfast.  The rice is slightly nutty, every individual grain is cooked to chewy perfection, and the grains stick together just enough to be edible with chopsticks. The bowl is remarkably consistent throughout, with no overcooked or undercooked spots. Mix the onsen egg in for a slightly richer, creamy blend.  The rest of the breakfast consists of a slice of fish and a variety of little sides. Each side, from the sweet, light tamago to the greens with mayo and pepper, is a delightful little world of flavor. Both the striped bass and the mackerel are tender and flaky with a subtle marinade and crispy skin.

The egg was the best decision ever - I personally enjoyed the swordfish more than the ___, it was the perfect mix of texture, fattiness, savoriness, and overall had better bite than the __ which was still delicious but just not as interesting of a fish. The tamago block was so good and so perfectly shaped (catering to my inner OCD I guess). Finally came by for Saturday brunch. This was a place I was very excited to try, but it really was just "a-ok." My friend and I had arrived just at little before 10AM and got seated right away. There are two tables of four seats flanking the entrance and a bar of four seats along the kitchen area. They serve the set meals with your choice of fish (I think for us it was some type of trout and some other fish's collar) and other toppings like ikura (fish roe) and onsen poached egg for additional cost.  I got the trout, and it was only alright. I had such high expectations listening to how they prepared it (wrapped in a type of leaf overnight and then cooked), but then when I tried it, it was not impressive at all. It was dry and bland. The size was also a little bit disappointing. For a main character for a dish set, it sure did not look like one. The fish almost got lost along with the other small sides. It didn't help that it was only about the size of index finger and middle finger together. The other sides were okay. I liked the tamagoyaki (that cube of egg custard) because the sweetness was subtle and not too much. It was also very egg-y. The miso soup was great as well with the radish they added. Rice was also great. Meal ranged from $32-35, when we went with no additional toppings.  Server was friendly. Restaurant was clean. Food was alright. Would likely not make the trek out here again. Definitely try to get here before 10:30AM to avoid too long of a wait, but they're also pretty good about calling parties up when they have seating opening up.

Chilly nights are better with exceptional ramen and DJ Shadow's 1996 LP, "Entroducing." The playlist was 90’s low key, intimate and chill, which created the perfect ambiance. I was in search of ramen and came upon Okonomi / Yuji Ramen. I came on a slow Sunday evening and didn’t wait more than a few minutes. Service was quick and before I knew it I was enjoying the spicy miso kotsu - tuna broth, tuna chasyu, aka miso, cilantro, sesame. This bowl was some of the best ramen!! The flavors were lovely, as were the noodles and and the tuna belly. The spice level is medium, not too spicy, but it does have some kick. The price point is a bit higher than some other ramen places, but I didn't mind because the experience was wonderful. Another thing to note is that they do not accept tips, so it all works out. I highly recommend Okonomi // Yuji Ramen.

We went here for breakfast on a Saturday morning. It’s best to come early, as the restaurant is tiny, with a small counter and two tables. Getting there when they opened at 9 spared us the crowds. The atmosphere is very tranquil and is a perfect complement to restorative Japanese food. Sitting at the bar, we were able to watch our food being prepared, and also enjoyed listening to new cooks being trained. Every dish, from the rice to the fish, was prepared with deep care and attention. The plating was excellent as well. Everything was delicately flavored and the umami provided the perfect counterbalance to our spicy dinner the night before.  The food comes as a set menu of miso soup, rice, vegetables, tea, and a choice of two types of fish. You can also add a poached egg to your rice, which provides a beautiful creaminess to the dish. The meal is pricey, so it won’t be replacing our bagels and yogurt anytime soon. However, it’s definitely a great spot to visit in Williamsburg and we will certainly return!

After trying to find comfort food for breakfast for a while, eventually I found this restaurant who serves comfort japanese food during breakfast and lunch. They only have one menu each day, normally they serve baked fish with vegetables, miso soup, japanese rice and boiled egg. This combination make me so comfy. The fish was well-cooked and firm (i think it was seasoned with japanese soya source). Will be back for sure to try other dishes. No tips required it is another good point.
Great food! Super fresh
Very small space serving uniquely flavored Ramen and Sushi. Get there early and they only seat full parties. Service is attentive.

Overpriced, $24 for a small portion of ramen.The variety was limited to fish-based ramen, and that's okay, but the ramen itself did not taste good at all. The noodles were undercooked and there was an egg shell in the broth. The broth left something to be desired.

Delish, seafood based alternative to pork ramen done right 👌. Non-ramen things were really good too.  Karashi nuta - was so good, was sad when it was finished.  Tunakotsu - tuna based ramen, really nice with the yuzu kosho and leeks. broth was really rich and tasty, and didn’t disappoint (i normally go with spicy ramens)  Spicy tuna - my friend got this, and this was REALLY good. would def get it next time!
Amazing food

(Translated by Google) A very small restaurant barely a dozen cutlery. So be prepared to wait if you go on weekends!  Very good ramen overall and a good price-quality ratio.  (Original) Un tout petit restaurant d'à peine une douzaine de couverts. Soyez donc prêts à attendre si vous y allez le weekend !  Très bon ramen dans l'ensemble et un rapport qualité-prix plutôt correct.

The wait is freakishly long but worth the wait. The Monte cristo was essentially french toast in a sandwich form. The eggs were fresh. The French toast platter is perfect for those who can't make up their mind as well. All in all I like it but don't think I can afford to wait that long again for a while.
Legit Japanese food

Dinner menu changes daily authentic Japanese food. The price of ramen is $16-24 they have 5 different choices and its worth the experience. The place is small so be prepared for 30 minute wait times be sure to try the sashimi appetizers aswell highly recommend it.
I had Japanese breakfast and it was good! But it is little bit over priced and they are usually sold out so not much options to choose from.
Best ramen I've ever had! Extremely friendly staff and beautiful small clean place. Open one in Montreal please!

Went for breakfast at Okonomi. The owner and chefs were nice. Decor is cozy and classy. The pickles were unique, more like Japanese fusion than traditional Japanese pickles, which I enjoyed. My only critique would be on the fish. I tried the fish belly marinated in miso and the collar bone seasoned with salt and pepper but they were both very under-seasoned. The quality of the fish was great, but there just wasn't much flavor to it. Another thing to note which hopefully can be addressed in the future, they don't provide you a napkin or cloth for your meal. Be prepared to be sneaking paper towels from the bathroom if you want to wipe your mouth. Considering the price of our meal, I expected a little more from Okonomi.

Wouldn't go back. On the plus side, the noodles were very good, as was the Bacon. On the other hand, the portions were tiny, the egg was too WAY soft for ramen (of any kind), they barely put anything besides noodles in the ramen, the wait was long, the place is cramped, and the service was kind of poor on the night we were there.  I enjoy sake though I don't keep track of the best ones I've had and I'm not particularly picky (even the cheap stuff is generally fine for me). I asked the waitress which sake was on the dry side and less sweet. She replied "All sakes are dry, the main difference is in how floral they are" in a tone that suggested she found it exasperating to explain sake to a clueless white guy. Nevermind that that is a silly statement about sake. So I just picked the house sake thinking that those are usually selected to have a broadly appealing flavor. Not only was it highly sweet, but it had a horrible flavor. I can say without a doubt that I  have never had a worse sake. The waitress never asked how it was even though it was not touched after the first sip.  Our water was not filled for a while so my girlfriend politely asked for more. She did other things and seemingly forgot. My girlfriend politely asked again 5 minutes later when the waitress was serving the couple next to us. She replied "I'll get it as soon as I put this down" in an extremely annoyed tone of voice. I guess this is the result when a restaurant raises prices and gets rid of tipping.
Excellent food and service!
Had traditional Japanese breakfast.  Extremely good.  Recommend you try during the week.  Otherwise be ready to wait!

I went there for a ‘Japanese breakfast’ on a weekday. It’s really small and cute space. The server was very chipper and friendly. The food was tasty, but it was also more like a $$$$ price range. Verbal only menu (was a set breakfast for us). A no tipping place. I’d give this a 3.5 / 5 because $70 USD for breakfast for 2 is not what I expected. Good food, trendy neighbourhood, but poor value. They serve barley tea, not coffee.
It's a small place but surprisingly good food
12 seats and awesome ramen. Sushi, too.

Pay attention! They serve and charge you the food you didn’t order. There’s a lot of small dishes in their meal set and they don’t even have a printed menu. You won’t figure out if one of the dishes is included in the meal set or not and they insist on charging you for the food you eat. The server was very rude and kept saying ‘But you ate it!’. Pay attention to your dishes and pay attention to your bill.

Absolutely love this place!! I came in for both the breakfast and dinner. Dinner was good, but my favourite was definitely the breakfast set meals. Was so good I came back every morning for the rest of my trip (and it wasn’t cheap either!). Pretty much tried everything on the menu (though they do change daily depending on what’s fresh). Highly recommend getting the uni and Onsen egg then mix it with the rice. It’s AMAZING!!! The fish is always fresh and extremely tender. The first day I had the salmon belly, and it was sooooo good!!! Will definitely be coming back when I visit Brooklyn!

We traveled from midtown to Brooklyn only to find out you had to be on a list.  When we got there at 1 the list was full and they closed at 3.  Not cool when it’s the only request your son has on a visit to nyc from Ca!

Was excited to try out this place that was filled with great review, but unfortunately it was not my style. The place was small but had very clean and warming atmosphere. Wait for the lunch was about 50minutes for us. With no set menu and price, we didn't know what we were gonna get. But after seeing the portion and tasting the dish, I think it is a bit overrated and pricy. I was thinking of more authentic Japanese flavors but it wasn't. Nothing really stood out for me flavor wise. I don't think I am coming back for more.
Went for breakfast, thoughtfully prepared, great service
had a ramen with monkfish liver broth, which was good. Didn't like the noodles though, too thin and without the consistency of ramen noodles. the appetizers were too expensive for what they are.
Best Japanese breakfast in New York, really cozy and small restaurant. The selection of sake by the glass is awesome.

This place is super tiny, but the food and atmosphere is amazing! I went on a date there and we sat at the bar. It really felt like we were in another country. The staff was super friendly and helpful.

Perfect meal. Gracious service, delicious authentic Japanese cuisine, it smells down the street (only breakfast foods until 3pm) then ramen at dinner time. You sit in communal settings, and can meet great new people, as I did!
I treat myself here for breakfast. Both the uni and egg are prepared excellently. I enjoy the fish collars as well.
Too expensive by far, but food is good.

Was really glad to have breakfast there on a weekday morning - it was cosy and peaceful without a queue. I also appreciated that there weren't any overt greetings of "irasshaimase" by the staff who kept things real and authentic in their own way - modern music and friendly banter. Food was amazing right from the warm barley drink to the perfectly cooked fish. I loved every moment of being there and would most definitely visit again.

I did not enjoy my meal here. The menu is limited which isn't necessarily a bad thing, but it lacked variety. Their ramen selection was all fish. It was strange there was no beef, pork, or chicken ramen option, only fish. I like fish, and the mackerel in the Shoyu Ramen I had was good, but a tad dry, even though it was in broth. The whole dish was missing something. One or two more ingredients would have made a huge difference. I was told really great things about this place, but that dish did not do it for me considering the price.

Sashimi is smallest I ever had, and it was with the skin, not sashimi grade by far. Sashimi is by standard made from the interior of the fish not the hard skin parts.  I have aten here when it opened and it was amazing, it has declined since. The food is ok still ok but the sashimi which sucked, like eating hard fish with the skin side and the brown hard part of the fish.

My husband and I came here for our wedding night dinner (we eloped in Brooklyn) and we are still raving about it nearly every day. The ramen....the best we have ever had!! Creamy broth, slight bite to the noodles, fresh fish, devine!  The sake selection was the most extensive we have come across. The staff are phenomenal, so knowledgeable and welcoming. I've been wanting to try the ramen here for quite some time, but I always ended up being in the area (for barber appointments) on the one day they are closed. Not so on a recent jaunt to the nabe! The dish looked fresh and diminutive, but the flavor was expressive and bigger than the bowl it's served in suggests. The space is cozy and intimate, and the attention paid to you by the line server may suffer a tiny bit as the restaurant gets packed and more busy. This is a good reason to really enjoy your food. Gratuity is politely declined on the bill.

Wonderful restaurant serving Japanese-style breakfast during the day time. Meal is served with fish entree (select from three options), multigrain rice with poached egg (add on), miso soup, and an assortment of small bite appetizers. The price of the meal includes gratuity (yay!). Staff are warm, friendly, and will ensure that you have a great dining experience!

I'd place this as one of the essential restaurants in NY you must visit. Their lunch menu is traditional Japanese breakfast with a high-end touch, amazingly cooked fish and vegetables. The flavor is very authentic, yet creative at the same time. Their dinner menu has a creative range of appetizers and REALLY, REALLY GOOD ramen. The special thing about the ramen is they use fish bones (from making fish for other dishes) in the broth. This is actually how a lot of ramen in Japan was made (with fish in the broth, but subtle), they just push it further and make the fish a prominent part of the broth. I can't say enough good things about this place. GO NOW!

(Translated by Google) Ordinary home cooking. Well cooked, but expensive compared to ordinary. Feeling priced high because of the good image of Japanese cuisine in the United States.  (Original) 평범한 가정식. 잘 요리 됐지만 평범함에 비해 비싸다. 미국에서 일본 요리에 대한 좋은 이미지 때문에 가격이 높게 책정된 느낌.
Delicious Ramen, excellent broth. Exquisite service in a very cozy location.
Mainly a fixed menu for "breakfast", the place is small... But the food and service are excellent and worth the trip.
Absolutely amazing! Best ramen I’ve had in the City, with fantastic service.

In the morning time they serve a set Japanese style breakfast with an option to choose your preferred fish for the entree and at nighttime this cozy restaurant turns into a ramen shop.  I visited in the morning time and was seated quickly, but with limited seating (12 seats) it is not surprising to find a line here. You are expected to share a table if necessary.  Precision and attention to details are always a part of Japanese culture so it was part of our expectation for our dishes as well. As a result the time it took for the staff to prepare the dishes was a bit long. Food tasted clean and balanced. Portion size is okay for the price you are paying. I did not feel full after the fact but was satisfied.  Also in sync with Japanese culture, tips are not expected post meal.
One of the top spots for Japanese food. The whole vibe is really nice. They really pay attention to detail.

Absolutely delicious, fresh, and authentic. The space is cozy but not cramped. There is a long wait time, we put our name down at 11:30am on a Saturday and got called in around 12:40. But it is worth it. Also, definitely get the poached egg add on.

First time eating authentic ramen and it was amazing seriously...its a small place and you might get others to sit with you which is not a bother because the food is a conversation starter alone...the sake (they do have options) is awesome..I wish I could take them with me when I move. I highly recommend this place. Not for large groups though.

Food is great though price is pretty steep for a place quite tucked into the urban space of Brooklyn. I had the grilled shark fatty belly and dang...it’s absolutely silky. My BFF has trout which is v good but you know it’s a fish easily …

Wonderful experience and albeit a bit pricey, the noodles are quite tasty. The Spicy Tuna mazeman was delish and had just the right amount of kick to em. Also, I would get the cheapest sake if you're on a budget. My wallet did not regret it and my tastebuds were ecstatic.

The place is small, the wait is long, and it's all worth it. Some of the best Japanese breakfast foods I've ever had, including in Japan, and amazing ramen too. Definetly recommend going for a demonstration if you don't mind spending a little extra on the experience, or just stopping in for breakfast if you don't mind a 30 minute wait. Either way it'll be worth your time and money for the high quality

Let me just say it’s the best restaurant I have been to in nyc. It’s small and the menu changes but everything you order is amazing. I am in love with this place, is a bit expensive but so worth it
Good ramen place in Brooklyn small but their ramen is on point pick anything from the menu you won't regret it
Tiny hipster digs! Had to wait a little to get seated but once I did, very intimate setting. Was hoping for the ramen to be a bit more broth-like, but still very tasty.
No the fish smells too bad. The appetizer tastes boring.

I came here to try this place after i got interested by how my friend described the food to me. We came in evening to try the ramen (because morning time is all about japanese traditional breakfast). The place was small but cozy, good …
Still my favorite spot in NY. When I enter this place I'm immediately brought to Kyoto, this place doesn't only satisfy your stomach but also your mind.

Like a trip to Japan. It is definitely my favorite place in the neighborhood. I have a small preference for the evening menu (ramen). The ramen are fish based cold or hot. All crazy good. lunch is a set menu with a choice of 3 fishes. Tiny place,  12 seats,  some wait if you don't get there early.

A bit overpriced for the quantity but the food was good, healthy and beautifully presented, everything you expect from ichiju-sansai meal. I liked the place, tiny with a true Japanese atmosphere. They don’t accept tips – which is really Japanese – I liked the spirit!
Yummy!!!

Don't understand the negative reviews of this place for being slow or communal seating. This is a true Japanese restaurant in terms of the vibe, decor and food. Very Waso inspired cuisine with local ingredients. If you just want oversalted tempura or ramen go somewhere else and don't sit with us.

My favorite ramen place! Totally worth the wait.

One of the best ramen places I have ever been. You may have to wait a little bit, but the blind barber is right next door, so you can just grab a quick drink while you wait. It is very, very cozy, but not in a bad way. Get the mesa ramen. I only had a taste, but it was amazing!

You won't find a beautiful Japanese breakfast like this in New York. I felt transported back to Japan! Their set breakfast includes tea, rice, fish, pickled veggies and an optional poached egg. You might be a little hungry after, but that's okay. It's still worth it.

Easily the best restaurant in the area, and one of my fav spots in the city. Excellent food made with care,  great service. Both breakfast and the ramen are so delicious. I am a regular and will continue to be! Yum

Amazing late night ramen - the paitan tuna was incredible. My partner had the uni miso mazemen, both bowls were incredible! Okonomi is set in a tiny space so that even off hours, the wait can be long (hour minimum). Came for a late lunch on Sunday, the food was understated, delicate and filling. Service was impeccable. Best Ramen in the neighborhood no doubt!! Very small but super cozy place with high level meals and delicious plump wine! There is a bar right on the corner if you have to wait for a table. Staff is extremely nice and knowledgeable! Tips are included in the price of the meal.

Really authentic and delicious Japanese food here. Excellent service as well. Be prepared to wait though as limited seats available. But you may walk around as you wait, they will contact you once your table is ready.

Love seafood? Then you'll love Yuji. I can still taste the mackerel sashimi with such a unique pairing of in house shoyu. The tunakatsu ramen will not be forgotten and revisited very soon! The nigori was the best I've tasted.
Absolutely delightful. Will be a regular spot.

"Okonomi" means "preference" in Japanese, a nice reference to Yuji Haraguchi's preference for sustainably sourced fish and the Japanese concept of "motainai", which means "no waste" ... the bones and other "waste" parts of the local fish that are served for breakfast and lunch at this tiny restaurant with just 5 counter seats and 8 table seats are then used to create the broth for the ramen served at night.  I've only been for breakfast/lunch, but there you're given a verbal menu, usually 2 or 3 fish options prepared simply and freshly. All are served as "teishoku", which means as a set meal with pickles, vegetables, miso soup, rice, and an egg omelet. Additions include an onsen tamago (poached egg in a house made soy dashi), sea urchin (when available), and assorted pickling experiments.  All dishes are beautifully prepared and plated. The shop cuts no corners on its tableware, glassware, or chopsticks/spoons. Really beautiful experience that we're lucky to have in NYC.  Kampai!

Had breakfast last Saturday which was so good! It was not only as beautiful as a piece of artwork but also yummy! Make sure you reserve your seats otherwise you have to wait for an hour as it only has about 12 seats.
